scended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Avicia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern Latinate form of   Alice .  It was borne by the British ballerina  Alicia Markova  (born  Lilian Alicia Marks ,  1910–2004 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Alisha","meanings":["Modern Latinate form of   Alice .  It was borne by the British ballerina  Alicia Markova  (born  Lilian Alicia Marks ,  1910–2004 )."]},{"name":"Alisia","meanings":["Modern Latinate form of   Alice .  It was borne by the British ballerina  Alicia Markova  (born  Lilian Alicia Marks ,  1910–2004 )."]},{"name":"Alyssa","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alissa ."]},{"name":"Alissa","meanings":["Contracted form of   Alicia ."]},{"name":"Alesha","meanings":["Respelling of   Alicia ."]}]},{"name":"Or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, T